The push/pull approach is a psychological methodology used to investigate the underlying motives and desires that drive behavior. It is predicated on the notion that people have evolved to have certain intrinsic needs or motives, such as a desire for food or safety. The push/pull method is used to measure these wants by determining how rapidly a person is willing to push or pull a joystick in response to various stimuli, such as pictures of food or images of danger. If participants push the experimental word "cake" quicker than the neutral word "window" with the joystick, it suggests that the word "cake" elicits a greater positive emotional response and a higher drive to approach it. It implies that the term "cake" connotes a positive result, such as joy or contentment. The speedier response to the word "cake" shows that it has a greater value in terms of the individual's goals and desires. 